##Is it right for men to be violent and for women to be rebellious?

Just fool around

She is just fooling around.

He hasn't left the neighborhood in over ten days. I put on my mask, goggles and gloves this afternoon and walked to side Park to skateboard.

I come in with my skateboard, and I skate. No contact with anyone during that time. The park was more crowded than expected today, and about four people were seen running without masks.

Sitting on the side of the road to rest, suddenly security came up, pointed out that I can not use this "car" in the park. I said it's a skateboard, not a car. He changed his story. No skateboarding in the park. My first thought was, this is ridiculous. Why shouldn't skateboarding be allowed in the park? Where did that come from?

I asked him to show me the rules, and he couldn't, and I said, "then go to your supervisor and tell me. ". I essentially feel that such a rule is unreasonable. In this case, if I was stopped by a security guard for not wearing a mask, I would be forgiven, but why not let me skateboard?

I figured I could skate away before he could lay down the law. He was quickly stopped by security. He just got in front of me (which was a very dangerous thing to do, because I could easily fall over) . Then I asked for the rules, and he still didn't show them. So I kept going, and if I wanted to slide forward to the door, I would just leave.

At this point, the security guard yelled at the back, "you're too young to be an old lady in the park. ". This sentence immediately caused me discomfort, I think should not be so insulting women, because insulting aunt is insulting me. As I slid back, I said, "why do you insult aunt like this? Isn't your mother an aunt? " Several other women heard me at the time. Later, I realized that they thought I was cursing the security guard, didn't realize I was defending all women.

I slid to the side of the runway near the door and stopped, ready to make my case to the guards and make what I thought was an unreasonable proposal. At this time that "scold aunt" security and other security guards have come around me, the formation is very big. The request I still made was: show me your written rules, but they still insisted that I go out. The written rules are outside the gate.

But I don't think they can kick me out until they see the rules. I said, this is a park. I'm a citizen. I filmed the whole thing on my phone, and they saw me doing it. One is to protect my own rights, the other is because I have been using video recording Beijing today.

As the crowd grew larger, a middle-aged man passing by who identified himself as a Beijinger began to scold me: "This is the kind of person who should have her arrested" , then proceeded to insult me further and start smashing my skateboard:

He smashed my skateboard twice, and it was accompanied by some pretty nasty insults like "fuck you. ". His wife echoed him: "How can you skateboard when you can't even take your three-year-old's car? ". I was surprised at his boorishness and became furious when he smashed my skateboard. Friends who know me well know that I love my skateboard very, very much, so much that every time I skate, I have to wipe it carefully after I go home. I can't bear to drop it.

I even tried to rush him, but I couldn't hit him. Even if I did, I'd be a lot weaker than him.

What made me most angry and sad was the fact that people around me were Poker Face, even acquiescing, to his behavior. No one thinks it's wrong for a man like that to treat a woman like that. Even I was repeatedly accused, including the previous hearing me to the security guard called him inappropriate language "aunt. ".

They all think the guy who smashed my skateboard was right, that I was violating public order. They felt that the rules should be accepted, and no one questioned whether they were reasonable.

At this point, a security guard finally took a picture of the "clear rules" and showed it to me. It's a little no-go sign at the door, and there's a little skateboard icon in the bottom row. I said yes right away and didn't insist on skating any more.

The Guy who smashed my skateboard, tried to go up and down again, but security stopped him. I also heard him say: "is holding a bellyful of anger no vent" , "is not only Hubei people should be scolded" , "I scolded you today hit your car how, big deal I broke compensate you" .

No one thinks he's wrong.

By then I was shaking with anger and the only thing I could think of was to call the police. As a result, people around me to the police response is: "The police are busy enough now, such as you, you have to disturb the police. ". My accusers include women. They didn't realize how helpless and scared I was in that situation.

By the time the police arrived, the man who had scolded me had gone. He walked between my phone and my head, and I watched, but no one thought he should stay. After hearing my statement, the policeman asked me, "What do you want? What can we do when he's gone? " I said I wanted an apology and compensation if the skateboard broke.

To check if the board was broken, I asked the security guard if I could skate 10 meters. The security guard nodded. When I started to skate, some people in the crowd scolded me for not allowing skateboarding in the park. My skateboard is worn but not broken. The police said if you still want to call the police, go with him to the police station.

I knew that going to the police station was a dead end, so I left the park.

I reflected on the whole thing. My only fault was my poor communication with the security guard, but this was based on my belief that the rule was unreasonable. I can apologize for my attitude.

When I got home, I was wiping my skateboard and crying. I even thought, I am already a very strong person, if is other weaker girls, is bullied when they how to do? When women and men are at odds, this physical inequality (even if I was a boxer) can feel very helpless, physically helpless. I was just trying to argue today, and people were just saying, "how can you be so awesome? Is Your Dad the Mayor of Beijing? "

No one thinks that, for whatever reason, men should not abuse and threaten women in this way. But whenever people see a woman arguing in public, they think she is a "shrew. ". That man may know that as long as he doesn't hit me, I can't do anything to him, but he can still damage my things (and rightly so: "You'll pay for it if you break it") , and he can still intimidate me by not touching my body, making me feel scared and threatened. And all those who watched, including those who watched on the road, took his side, acquiescing to his right to use violence. They all tacitly side with the more powerful, but never question whether there is anything wrong with power itself. They will not understand that I am not "undermining" order, but rather defending our common rights.

Since the afternoon, I've been struggling to cope with my disappointment and sadness. It's as if I've read Lu Xun's scenario in a textbook and stepped back into the present. I've seen firsthand how bad society has become. As my good friend Xiaoxian says, the worst is not even the virus, but the psychological state distorted by fear. This is something that will not change even after the epidemic is over. "people only know how to transfer their rights, " she said. "In fact, when you transfer your rights, no one takes you seriously. Look at the Hubei people who have been saving themselves. ".

I think of the Hubei people who were discriminated against, the people who were forced to be segregated, the people who were discriminated against because they couldn't buy masks but had to go out, the people who were sued for violating their right of reputation after being sexually assaulted, people who are somehow deprived of their lives just because they are living their daily lives and doing their daily work. They could all be us. But no one here today, including the women, realized that I could be one of them.

The day I brought this skateboard home was one of the best moments of my life
